# Documentation Location Rules

All product, SDK, guide, API, reference, deployment, and example documentation must live in the single top-level `docs/` website.

## Required Location

- Use `docs/src/content/docs/` for documentation pages.
- Use `docs/astro.config.mjs` for documentation navigation and Starlight configuration.
- Use `docs/src/assets/`, `docs/src/styles/`, and `docs/public/` only for documentation-site assets.
- Do not create another documentation folder anywhere in the repository.

## Prohibited Locations

- Do not add new documentation files outside `docs/`.
- Do not create `README.md`, `docs/`, `documentation/`, `wiki/`, `guides/`, `examples/*/README.md`, or similar docs locations outside the top-level `docs/` website.
- Do not add SDK usage guides, API references, tutorials, migration notes, architecture docs, or deployment notes inside Go package directories, example directories, scripts, or root-level ad hoc files.
- Do not edit generated documentation output in `docs/dist/`, `docs/.astro/`, or `docs/node_modules/`.

## Existing Outside-Docs Files

- Treat existing root or example README files as legacy entry points only.
- Do not expand existing outside-docs README content with new documentation.
- If information in an outside-docs README needs to grow, move the real documentation into `docs/src/content/docs/` and keep the outside file minimal or link-only when explicitly requested.

